		<p>Hi William,</p>
<p>Thanks so much for the comment. The irony that you&#8217;d mention Blippy just before my scathing article about it is simply a killer coincidence. :)</p>
<p>To be fair, I see a lot of benefit to keeping the world connected through social networks. As the United Nations Development Program&#8217;s Internet Communication Technology Digital Opportunity Initiative showed back in 2001, the <a href="http://3nw.com/doi/04_conclusions/4_conclusions.htm" rel="nofollow">benefits of people who communicate regularly bring higher income and more peace to all</a>. (very rapid summation of a complex theory) So what that means is that I can get back in contact with people from Australia or Tokyo I met back in the early 1990s all with a simple name lookup. If they want to talk to me, super cool!</p>
<p>However&#8230; The secret is in the usage of the data. Visibility into the EULAs and when they change EULA is what separate business from nonprofit. The more people share, the more they are vulnerable to marketing as well as cybercrime. One is legal, the other is not so much. </p>
<p>I think Facebook will adapt or it will turn into the next Bebo / Friendster / Myspace and fade off into oblivion. </p>
<p>Charles</p>

		
